Interesting! When we send `SENSE TEMP 51`, the firmware responds with `ACT HEATER ON` instead of `ACT HEATER OFF`. This is a bug in my controller logic. Let me trace through what should happen:

1. We send SENSE TEMP 46 (< 47, so heater ON) ✓
2. We send SENSE TEMP 51 (50 <= 51 <= 52, and temp is rising from 46 to 51, so should trigger early OFF)

But the controller is responding with HEATER ON instead of OFF. Let me check my logic again:

Looking at my code:
```c
} else if (input.temperature_c >= CONTROLLER_TEMP_EARLY_OFF_THRESHOLD &&
           input.temperature_c <= CONTROLLER_TEMP_HIGH_THRESHOLD) {
    /* 50 <= TEMP <= 52: check if temperature is rising */
    bool temp_rising = controller->has_valid_sensor &&
                       (input.temperature_c > controller->last_temperature_c);
    if (temp_rising) {
        /* Temperature rising: turn heater OFF early, treat as HOLDING */
        controller_set_holding(controller, false);
```

The issue is that `controller->last_temperature_c` is being set BEFORE the control logic runs. Let me check:

```c
case CONTROLLER_INPUT_TEMPERATURE:
    controller->has_valid_sensor = true;
    controller->last_temperature_c = input.temperature_c;  // <-- This updates it first!
    controller->last_valid_sensor_ms = input.now_ms;
```

So when we check `input.temperature_c > controller->last_temperature_c`, the last_temperature_c has already been updated to the current value, so the comparison is always false!

I need to save the old temperature before updating:

